WEBVTT

00:03.699 --> 00:04.047
.

00:04.091 --> 00:06.049
- Sometimes you gotta choose
between being respected

00:06.093 --> 00:07.311
and being liked.

00:07.355 --> 00:09.487
- You told her to stick
her neck out.

00:09.531 --> 00:13.361
- You continue to prove
you can't stay in your lane.

00:13.404 --> 00:14.710
- 'Cause you've been running
this joint

00:14.753 --> 00:16.581
like a drive-through car wash
since I got here.

00:16.625 --> 00:18.409
We supposed to
be helping people.

00:18.453 --> 00:19.802
- You had a fair amount
of experience with

00:19.845 --> 00:22.065
bureaucracy in your old job?
- Some years ago

00:22.109 --> 00:24.459
stray bullet hit
a 14-year-old boy.

00:24.502 --> 00:26.461
By some miracle, he survived.

00:26.504 --> 00:29.029
It's what drew me to medicine.

00:29.072 --> 00:30.465
- You been taking your meds?

00:30.508 --> 00:32.684
- I can take care of myself.

00:32.728 --> 00:35.861
- But Mom...please, we've got
to get you off the streets.

00:35.905 --> 00:39.126
- Dr. Cooper has gotten
some very fat perks

00:39.169 --> 00:41.519
since he started
boosting the Vascon.

00:41.563 --> 00:44.348
- The more devices the hospital
buys, the bigger his kickback.

00:44.392 --> 00:46.829
So I make him think
I'd do anything for money.

00:47.569 --> 00:48.918
- It's great.
It's beautiful.

00:48.961 --> 00:50.050
I mean, the beaches are...

00:50.093 --> 00:51.181
I mean, they just go
on forever.

00:51.225 --> 00:52.835
The water is so blue.

00:52.878 --> 00:54.489
- Morning, Matt.

00:54.532 --> 00:58.101
- Will, my good man!
Thank you.

00:58.145 --> 00:59.537
- Little upgrade there?

00:59.581 --> 01:01.278
- Oh, yeah.
[chuckles]

01:01.322 --> 01:03.106
- [exhales]
Man.

01:03.150 --> 01:05.369
That is sweet.

01:05.413 --> 01:07.763
- Thanks.
Did you catch that Bears game?

01:07.806 --> 01:10.461
- No, I missed it.
- Oh, oh, you missed...

01:10.505 --> 01:12.028
- Yeah?
- So good.

01:12.072 --> 01:14.161
- I was at
a buddy's poker night.

01:14.204 --> 01:15.640
Big mistake.

01:15.684 --> 01:16.728
- You hungover?

01:16.772 --> 01:18.861
- No, worse.
Man, I lost my shirt.

01:18.904 --> 01:22.473
Bought in way beyond my means.
- It happens.

01:22.517 --> 01:26.390
- Yeah, it's just the last
thing I need right now.

01:26.434 --> 01:27.913
You know, I'm still
paying back college,

01:27.957 --> 01:29.393
med school, credit cards...

01:29.437 --> 01:31.134
- Yeah, yeah.
Yeah, I've been there.

01:31.178 --> 01:33.223
- Not in quite a while.

01:33.267 --> 01:35.965
- Yeah, I'm doing all right
in the moment.

01:36.008 --> 01:38.185
- Yeah, I'd say.
Any tips?

01:38.228 --> 01:41.753
'Cause I'm about ready to start
picking up the graveyard shift.

01:41.797 --> 01:44.756
- You're desperate, huh?
- Well, how could you tell?

01:44.800 --> 01:48.238
- Wow.
Okay, let me think about it.

01:48.282 --> 01:51.546
Hey, listen, I gotta run
to make my 7:00,

01:51.589 --> 01:55.289
but I'll see you, Will, okay?
- Yeah, see you.

01:55.332 --> 01:58.596
[tense music]

01:58.640 --> 02:01.904
♪

02:08.606 --> 02:09.868
- If you're not going
to order something,

02:09.912 --> 02:12.175
you're gonna have to leave.
I need the booth.

02:12.219 --> 02:13.698
- Why don't we try that again?

02:13.742 --> 02:16.136
But this time let's start
with a "Good morning!

02:16.179 --> 02:17.528
What can I get you?"

02:17.572 --> 02:19.574
And throw in a smile,
just to really sell it.

02:19.617 --> 02:21.750
- [sighs]
Gosh, I'm sorry.

02:21.793 --> 02:23.447
I didn't mean to--
- Two coffees.

02:23.491 --> 02:26.929
Black.
And bring back a couple menus.

02:28.670 --> 02:30.672
Hi.

02:34.980 --> 02:36.678
I brought you a three-month
supply of your meds.

02:36.721 --> 02:39.724
I know you don't like taking
them, but you need to, Mom.

02:39.768 --> 02:43.467
- How about...we make
a little deal?

02:43.511 --> 02:47.819
I'll take them
if you loan me $1,200.

02:47.863 --> 02:49.952
For the van,
so I can get it running again.

02:49.995 --> 02:51.214
- [sighs]

02:51.258 --> 02:53.347
I'd rather give you the money
for rent.

02:53.390 --> 02:56.306
- Don't start with that again.

02:56.350 --> 02:58.526
- You need a roof
over your head.

02:58.569 --> 03:01.137
Heat, running water.
- Maybe you need all that,

03:01.181 --> 03:02.356
but I don't.

03:02.399 --> 03:06.229
Survived plenty of winters
in the van.

03:06.273 --> 03:07.578
If you don't want to spot me
the cash--

03:07.622 --> 03:10.364
- No, it's--it's not
that I don't want to.

03:10.407 --> 03:12.801
- You just wanna
call the shots.

03:12.844 --> 03:15.195
Tell me how to use it.

03:15.238 --> 03:18.198
[somber music]

03:18.241 --> 03:20.200
Just forget it.

03:20.243 --> 03:21.375
- No, Mom, wait!

03:21.418 --> 03:22.941
What about breakfast?

03:22.985 --> 03:26.467
♪

03:26.510 --> 03:28.860
- I don't want to stay
anywhere I'm not wanted.

03:28.904 --> 03:33.561
♪

03:33.604 --> 03:35.127
- [sighs]

03:35.171 --> 03:36.694
- How's it going?
- Yeah.

03:36.738 --> 03:40.263
There you go.
There he is.

03:40.307 --> 03:41.482
What's up, Dylan?

03:41.525 --> 03:43.005
- Hey, what up, Kev?
- Uh-huh.

03:43.048 --> 03:46.530
- You show up late
to surgery too...Doc?

03:46.574 --> 03:49.446
- And good morning to you, sis.

03:49.490 --> 03:52.710
What we playing, man?
- Oh, we playing 21.

03:52.754 --> 03:54.408
- Ay, don't look at me.
I'm not getting in the middle

03:54.451 --> 03:56.845
of that Scott sibling beef.
- Anyway...

03:56.888 --> 03:59.587
you sure you want to dirty
those pretty fingernails, D?

03:59.630 --> 04:03.243
Gotta keep them clean, case
you gotta cut someone open.

04:03.286 --> 04:05.549
- Smart-ass.
- So back to the bust.

04:05.593 --> 04:09.466
Simultaneous breaches.
Three houses, same block.

04:09.510 --> 04:11.555
Bam! We knock the door
off the hinges.

04:11.599 --> 04:12.904
So we coming through, right?

04:12.948 --> 04:14.558
[gunshot]

04:14.602 --> 04:16.604
- Yo, that was gunfire.

04:16.647 --> 04:18.345
- Damn right that was gunfire.

04:18.388 --> 04:20.303
[suspenseful music]

04:20.347 --> 04:21.565
- Third floor, Kev.
- I'll call it in.

04:21.609 --> 04:23.175
- All right.
- 911,

04:23.219 --> 04:26.657
this is Officer Kevin Atwater.
Badge number 52784.

04:26.701 --> 04:28.703
Shots fired on the inside of
the southwest corner building

04:28.746 --> 04:31.271
on Damen and Pershing.
Roll some cars this way.

04:31.314 --> 04:32.924
You ready?

04:32.968 --> 04:35.753
Let's go.

04:35.797 --> 04:39.583
♪

04:39.627 --> 04:41.759
- Nah, man.
No way you're coming in.

04:41.803 --> 04:43.848
You're not even armed.
- I'll be all right.

04:43.892 --> 04:47.417
- You need to stand down.
You are not the police anymore.

04:47.461 --> 04:54.598
♪

04:59.255 --> 05:01.344
- Chicago PD, big guy.
You okay?

05:01.388 --> 05:02.389
Huh?

05:02.432 --> 05:03.999
Everything all right?

05:04.042 --> 05:05.348
Hey!

05:05.392 --> 05:12.486
♪

05:15.619 --> 05:17.186
- Hold tight, we're gonna get
you some help, okay?

05:17.229 --> 05:19.057
- [crying]
- Zora?

05:19.101 --> 05:21.364
Zora?
- D, over here!

05:21.408 --> 05:22.626
We're gonna get you some help,
all right?

05:22.670 --> 05:23.932
You're doing good,
you're doing good, okay?

05:23.975 --> 05:26.238
Tender age male victim,
GSW to abdomen,

05:26.282 --> 05:27.457
smaller caliber round.
- [gasps]

05:27.501 --> 05:29.894
- We're on the third floor.

05:34.029 --> 05:35.639
- Oh, hey, little man.
You mind moving your hand

05:35.683 --> 05:37.772
so I can take a look?
I'm a doctor.

05:37.815 --> 05:39.164
Oh.

05:39.208 --> 05:41.732
♪

05:41.776 --> 05:43.560
- Ow!
- I know it hurts, I know.

05:43.604 --> 05:45.127
What happened here?

05:45.170 --> 05:47.477
- We were just playing around.

05:47.521 --> 05:49.610
He wouldn't really mean
to shoot me.

05:49.653 --> 05:51.568
He was being a super villain.

05:51.612 --> 05:54.354
The bullets were gonna bounce
right off me.

05:54.397 --> 05:56.007
- Hey.
Hey, hey!

05:56.051 --> 05:58.445
Stay with me--uh-uh.
Open your eyes, come on.

05:58.488 --> 06:00.142
There you go, huh?
What's your name?

06:00.185 --> 06:01.361
- Michael.
- Okay, Michael.

06:01.404 --> 06:02.884
I know it's hard, Michael.
Hey, Michael!

06:02.927 --> 06:05.060
Michael, I know it's hard,
but you gotta stay with me.

06:05.103 --> 06:06.104
You gotta stay awake.

06:06.148 --> 06:07.671
Zora, how long
on that ambulance?

06:07.715 --> 06:10.239
- He said ten minutes.

06:10.282 --> 06:11.675
♪

06:11.719 --> 06:13.285
- Come on.
Hey, stay with me.

06:13.329 --> 06:14.896
Come on.

06:14.939 --> 06:16.724
Hey, hey.

06:16.767 --> 06:18.378
Oh, God.

06:18.421 --> 06:20.205
Stay with me.

06:20.249 --> 06:24.732
♪

06:28.475 --> 06:28.866
.

06:28.910 --> 06:30.694
- Ow!
[crying]

06:30.738 --> 06:32.217
- No retained bullets.

06:32.261 --> 06:34.350
- Dr. Scott, the trauma
attending is still in surgery.

06:34.394 --> 06:36.047
He'll meet the team
up in the OR

06:36.091 --> 06:38.006
after they get Michael prepped.
- Finish this unit of blood

06:38.049 --> 06:39.703
and get him on
the transport monitor.

06:39.747 --> 06:41.052
- Mommy...

06:41.096 --> 06:42.663
- Hey, your parents
are on the way right now,

06:42.706 --> 06:44.012
champ, all right?
We'll take you up

06:44.055 --> 06:46.797
for a little operation.
- No, no, no.

06:46.841 --> 06:48.016
- Hey, relax.
You're gonna be asleep

06:48.059 --> 06:49.017
the whole time.
You won't feel a thing.

06:49.060 --> 06:50.627
- Asleep?
- Yeah.

06:50.671 --> 06:51.846
The surgeon's gonna look
inside your belly

06:51.889 --> 06:53.369
and fix what's broken.

06:53.413 --> 06:56.285
And, if there's time,
I'm gonna tell him

06:56.328 --> 06:58.156
to put some superpowers
inside of you

06:58.200 --> 06:59.854
before they stitch you back up.

06:59.897 --> 07:01.638
Okay.
All right.

07:01.682 --> 07:03.988
All right, come on.
Let's go.

07:04.032 --> 07:07.209
[dramatic music]

07:07.252 --> 07:10.473
♪

07:10.517 --> 07:12.910
See you later, sis.
- Yeah, course, do your thing.

07:12.954 --> 07:14.172
Ay, good work, D.

07:14.216 --> 07:16.479
- Good morning, everybody.

07:16.523 --> 07:19.482
By now, you all should've
received emails

07:19.526 --> 07:21.745
with your credentials
for the new online portal,

07:21.789 --> 07:23.921
Patients Pro, okay?

07:23.965 --> 07:25.880
If it's not in your inbox,
check your spam.

07:25.923 --> 07:28.099
If it's not in your spam,
I guess...I don't know,

07:28.143 --> 07:30.450
assume you've been fired.

07:30.493 --> 07:33.496
You will be using this system
to log how much time you spend

07:33.540 --> 07:36.020
with each patient from now on.

07:36.064 --> 07:38.806
Special Forces has a slogan...

07:38.849 --> 07:41.243
"Slow is smooth
and smooth is fast."

07:41.286 --> 07:44.551
In other words, we need
to be deliberate and tactical

07:44.594 --> 07:46.291
in our approach to medicine.

07:46.335 --> 07:50.252
The more patients we're able
to see, the more lives we save.

07:50.295 --> 07:53.647
Oh, and as an added bonus,
whoever ends the month

07:53.690 --> 07:57.564
with the highest turnover rate,
will enjoy an executive suite

07:57.607 --> 08:00.828
at the United Center,
watching the Blackhawks game

08:00.871 --> 08:02.264
of their choosing.

08:02.307 --> 08:03.439
Not bad, huh?

08:03.483 --> 08:06.486
All right, let's get going.
Thank you.

08:06.529 --> 08:08.531
- Not a Blackhawks fan,
Dr. Charles?

08:08.575 --> 08:10.228
- Oh, huge Hawks fan.

08:10.272 --> 08:12.274
Not a big fan
of incentive-based medicine.

08:12.317 --> 08:15.016
- [laughs]
- I mean, fast is slow,

08:15.059 --> 08:17.758
but smooth--sorry, I don't know
what that means.

08:17.801 --> 08:19.673
- [laughs]
- I don't.

08:19.716 --> 08:21.109
- Hey, can I ask you something?

08:21.152 --> 08:22.719
- Hey, Maggie?
- Yep.

08:22.763 --> 08:25.548
- Can I tempt you away
from your brick?

08:25.592 --> 08:26.767
- Yeah.
- Ah, Dr. Hammer,

08:26.810 --> 08:30.335
you too, as well.

08:30.379 --> 08:33.469
Listen, Elaine Foster
is on her way here.

08:33.513 --> 08:36.385
She suffered a minor fall
at her home.

08:36.428 --> 08:38.561
And her husband, Jim,
is driving her here.

08:38.605 --> 08:41.172
- Elaine and Jim Foster--
big-time moneybags.

08:41.216 --> 08:44.567
- No, no, they are two
of our most generous funders.

08:44.611 --> 08:47.048
I've mingled over the years
with the Fosters

08:47.091 --> 08:49.616
at donor events.
They're really good people.

08:49.659 --> 08:51.139
Very down-to-earth.

08:51.182 --> 08:53.707
Anyway, I'd like the two of you
to look out for them

08:53.750 --> 08:55.317
while they're in the ED.

08:55.360 --> 08:59.713
And I'll stop in to see Elaine
once she's settled in.

08:59.756 --> 09:03.281
Thank you.

09:03.325 --> 09:05.414
- VIPs aren't your cup of tea,
I take it?

09:05.457 --> 09:08.809
- I like them--
just from a distance.

09:08.852 --> 09:11.246
- Didn't you rub elbows all the
time with the rich and fabulous

09:11.289 --> 09:13.248
over in Grosse Pointe?
- Yeah, hence my reluctance.

09:13.291 --> 09:15.467
[beeping]
- Well, heads-up,

09:15.511 --> 09:17.339
'cause here they are.

09:17.382 --> 09:19.994
Mr. and Mrs. Foster,
we're going to treatment six.

09:20.037 --> 09:23.040
- All right.

09:25.086 --> 09:26.827
- How did the fall happen,
Mrs. Foster?

09:26.870 --> 09:29.351
- Oh, Elaine, please.

09:29.394 --> 09:32.615
I got home and smelled
something burning--ow!

09:32.659 --> 09:33.834
[gasps]
- Sorry.

09:33.877 --> 09:36.140
- Uh-oh.
- It's okay.

09:36.184 --> 09:39.361
I'm just being a big baby.

09:39.404 --> 09:42.233
Anyway, I hightailed it
to the kitchen.

09:42.277 --> 09:44.932
And tripped over
my own two feet.

09:44.975 --> 09:47.021
- Happens to me almost daily.

09:47.064 --> 09:49.458
- Well, it turns out Jim here
was heating up

09:49.501 --> 09:51.373
some leftover pizza.

09:51.416 --> 09:53.680
He didn't even smell
that the house was about

09:53.723 --> 09:55.029
to burn down.

09:55.072 --> 09:56.639
He must've had COVID.

09:56.683 --> 09:59.207
Isn't that one
of the long-term side effects?

09:59.250 --> 10:01.078
- I never had COVID.

10:01.122 --> 10:04.038
It's not my fault
you're a klutz.

10:04.081 --> 10:06.518
- Honey, I wasn't blaming you.

10:06.562 --> 10:09.521
[tense music]

10:09.565 --> 10:11.872
♪

10:11.915 --> 10:14.396
So what do you think,
Dr. Hammer?

10:14.439 --> 10:17.486
Am I going to keep the leg?
- Prognosis is good.

10:17.529 --> 10:19.314
I don't think that it's broken,
but we're gonna get an x-ray

10:19.357 --> 10:20.750
to check it out.
- I'm peckish.

10:20.794 --> 10:23.623
We've donated a small fortune
to this hospital.

10:23.666 --> 10:25.668
It'd be nice if you could
offer us a snack.

10:25.712 --> 10:28.845
- Jim, why don't you go grab
something from the cafeteria?

10:28.889 --> 10:32.544
- Fine.
Honey, you want anything?

10:32.588 --> 10:34.111
- No, thanks.

10:34.155 --> 10:37.811
♪

10:37.854 --> 10:39.900
I'm sorry about him.

10:39.943 --> 10:42.293
He's been a bit
out of sorts lately.

10:42.337 --> 10:44.426
- That's okay.
Don't worry about it.

10:44.469 --> 10:46.602
- We'll be back shortly
to take you for that x-ray.

10:46.646 --> 10:50.911
♪

10:50.954 --> 10:52.434
- That was odd.

10:52.477 --> 10:55.655
Goodwin's usually an excellent
judge of character.

10:55.698 --> 10:57.308
I mean, maybe
it's like Elaine said;

10:57.352 --> 10:59.702
maybe he's just having
a bad day.

10:59.746 --> 11:01.835
- Or maybe he's on his best
behavior at donor events,

11:01.878 --> 11:04.141
but around us mere mortals--
- Mere mortals?

11:04.185 --> 11:07.492
Speak for yourself.
- [laughs]

11:09.190 --> 11:12.889
[alarm beeping]

11:12.933 --> 11:14.717
- We're going to Baghdad.
- Candace Mason.

11:14.761 --> 11:15.892
31-year-old female.

11:15.936 --> 11:17.764
Pedestrian struck at low speed.

11:17.807 --> 11:19.200
No loss of consciousness.

11:19.243 --> 11:21.593
C-spine cleared in the field.
Vitals are stable.

11:21.637 --> 11:23.857
And pain confined to
her left elbow.

11:23.900 --> 11:26.903
- Hi, I'm Dr. Halstead.
And this here is Dr. Scott.

11:26.947 --> 11:28.775
- I swear, I looked both ways
before I crossed the street.

11:28.818 --> 11:30.298
I'm sure I did.

11:30.341 --> 11:32.256
I don't know how I didn't see
that car coming at me.

11:32.300 --> 11:34.128
- That's okay.
We gotcha.

11:34.171 --> 11:36.304
All right, transfer on three.

11:36.347 --> 11:40.264
Ready?
One, two, three.

11:40.308 --> 11:43.746
- Oh, my God.
Candace Mason?

11:43.790 --> 11:49.056
I have to tell you,
your website saved my life.

11:49.099 --> 11:52.189
Reading about your journey
with Lupus...

11:52.233 --> 11:56.150
it finally inspired me
to see a doctor.

11:56.193 --> 11:58.326
Are--are you okay?

11:58.369 --> 12:00.110
I read on the newsletter
you were having a flare-up?

12:00.154 --> 12:01.982
- Ah, yes, I am,
but that's not why I'm here.

12:02.025 --> 12:05.159
I was in a minor accident.
- Take good care of her.

12:05.202 --> 12:08.510
She's an angel.

12:08.553 --> 12:10.860
- So you're having
a Lupus flare-up.

12:10.904 --> 12:12.340
What medications
are you taking?

12:12.383 --> 12:14.777
- I'm not taking
any medications.

12:14.821 --> 12:17.780
- But if you're in a flare-up--
- Right, um...

12:17.824 --> 12:19.826
anything I tell you
in regards to my health

12:19.869 --> 12:22.089
is protected by
patient confidentiality, right?

12:22.132 --> 12:24.265
- Yes, that's right.

12:24.308 --> 12:26.441
- I'm not in the middle
of a flare-up.

12:26.484 --> 12:28.008
I know what I said
to that woman,

12:28.051 --> 12:30.575
but my Lupus
isn't currently active.

12:30.619 --> 12:33.404
Truth is I've been
in remission...

12:33.448 --> 12:36.277
for almost five years.

12:36.320 --> 12:38.670
♪

12:38.714 --> 12:41.717
- Okay, Dr. Taylor, shoot.
Ask me anything.

12:41.761 --> 12:45.547
- I was hoping you'd give me
feedback on my ten-year plan.

12:45.590 --> 12:48.637
- I'm sorry, did you just say
"ten-year plan"?

12:48.680 --> 12:52.162
As in a full-on decade
of planning?

12:57.907 --> 12:59.648
Oh, wow.

12:59.691 --> 13:01.998
You wrote it out.

13:02.042 --> 13:03.347
Binder and everything.

13:03.391 --> 13:05.610
- You think I'd cut corners?

13:05.654 --> 13:08.831
- You always been
so future-oriented?

13:08.875 --> 13:12.704
- No, actually.
Kind of the opposite.

13:12.748 --> 13:16.012
I spent a lot of my early years
looking backwards.

13:16.056 --> 13:18.623
- Backwards?

13:18.667 --> 13:21.888
- Oh, well, um...

13:21.931 --> 13:23.454
I'm adopted.

13:23.498 --> 13:26.414
So I just had a lot
of questions in regards

13:26.457 --> 13:27.763
to my origins, I guess.

13:27.807 --> 13:30.461
I didn't know anything
about my birth parents.

13:30.505 --> 13:32.855
But once I accepted I wasn't
going to get any answers,

13:32.899 --> 13:36.250
I decided to focus all
of my energy ahead instead.

13:36.293 --> 13:38.818
- Oh.
Yeah, I get that.

13:38.861 --> 13:40.341
Makes sense.

13:40.384 --> 13:42.082
Me, I tend to ride the wave.

13:42.125 --> 13:43.605
See where life takes me,
you know?

13:43.648 --> 13:45.694
- I can't say I've ever let
life take the lead.

13:45.737 --> 13:48.131
- Oh, well, whether you let it
or not, it's gonna throw you

13:48.175 --> 13:51.004
some curveballs.
And in my experience...

13:51.047 --> 13:55.922
planning leads to expectations.
And expectations, they can, uh,

13:55.965 --> 13:57.358
lead to disappointments.
Yeah?

13:57.401 --> 13:59.099
- Dr. Marcel, could you take
a look at the patient

13:59.142 --> 14:00.317
in treatment 3?

14:00.361 --> 14:01.579
- What's the problem?
- I don't know.

14:01.623 --> 14:03.886
I didn't intake her.
Just know she's refusing

14:03.930 --> 14:07.629
to speak with anyone
until she sees a doctor.

14:07.672 --> 14:09.936
- Yeah, okay.
I'll be right there.

14:09.979 --> 14:12.286
Sorry, I gotta cut it short.
- Actually, if you don't mind,

14:12.329 --> 14:14.288
I would love to tag along.

14:14.331 --> 14:18.727
- No, not at all.
- Cool.

14:18.770 --> 14:20.294
- Hey there, Ms. Hawley.

14:20.337 --> 14:23.471
I'm Dr. Marcel.
This is Dr. Taylor.

14:23.514 --> 14:25.821
How can we help?
- Hi, it's Gina.

14:25.865 --> 14:30.260
- You can take
the scarf off now.

14:30.304 --> 14:32.045
- I'll close the curtain.

14:32.088 --> 14:33.481
- She didn't wanna come in.

14:33.524 --> 14:36.310
I practically had to drag her
to my car.

14:36.353 --> 14:37.833
- You're her...
- Best friend.

14:37.877 --> 14:39.530
I left Chicago at the height
of the pandemic

14:39.574 --> 14:41.532
and just got back last week.

14:41.576 --> 14:42.925
If I had known
what was going on...

14:42.969 --> 14:44.231
- Liza, I feel fine, really.

14:44.274 --> 14:45.797
- You are not fine.

14:45.841 --> 14:47.234
You have to show them.

14:47.277 --> 14:49.976
[somber music]

14:50.019 --> 14:53.501
- Well, listen, Gina,
if it's any comfort,

14:53.544 --> 14:56.852
we've seen every wart, boil,
cyst known to man.

14:56.896 --> 14:59.681
So you've got nothing to be
embarrassed about here.

14:59.724 --> 15:06.644
♪

15:10.822 --> 15:13.434
Uh-huh.

15:16.567 --> 15:16.785
.

15:16.828 --> 15:19.396
- Remember when I said Cooper
was getting consulting fees

15:19.440 --> 15:22.138
from Vasik and various
other companies?

15:22.182 --> 15:25.663
Well, I started looking
at those other companies.

15:25.707 --> 15:29.885
And I found some peculiar
things like stock photos

15:29.929 --> 15:33.410
on their websites, contact
numbers that are connected

15:33.454 --> 15:35.630
to overseas call centers.

15:35.673 --> 15:37.893
So I got in touch
with one of my friends

15:37.937 --> 15:41.375
who's a wealth manager.
Asked him to do some digging.

15:41.418 --> 15:44.291
And it turns out
they're shell companies.

15:44.334 --> 15:46.989
- So Vasik set them up
as a cover.

15:47.033 --> 15:49.992
- Anyway, how'd it go
this morning?

15:50.036 --> 15:53.561
- I cried broke, but I'm not
sure Cooper took the bait.

15:53.604 --> 15:54.997
[knocking at door]

15:55.041 --> 15:56.303
Hey, we're gonna nail him,
Ms. Goodwin.

15:56.346 --> 15:57.826
- Come in.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

15:57.869 --> 15:59.523
I didn't mean to interrupt.
- I gotta get back

15:59.567 --> 16:00.872
to the ED anyway.
- All right.

16:00.916 --> 16:02.874
Thank you for stopping by,
Dr. Halstead.

16:02.918 --> 16:04.833
- Yep.

16:04.876 --> 16:06.313
- So where are you guys
at with this thing?

16:06.356 --> 16:08.532
You got enough evidence yet
to go to the authorities?

16:08.576 --> 16:10.012
- Unfortunately, no.

16:10.056 --> 16:12.319
What I told you about
the shell companies--

16:12.362 --> 16:16.714
well, there's no way to prove
that Vasik was behind them

16:16.758 --> 16:19.761
without being able to look
at their books.

16:19.804 --> 16:22.633
- Look, Sharon, I know
how important this is to you.

16:22.677 --> 16:24.331
I do.
But much more importantly,

16:24.374 --> 16:25.941
I'm worried about
your stress levels.

16:25.985 --> 16:27.334
I mean, it's not like you don't
have other things going on

16:27.377 --> 16:28.857
in your life, you know?

16:28.900 --> 16:31.251
- I'm really taking care
of myself.

16:31.294 --> 16:32.600
- Really?

16:32.643 --> 16:35.081
What's your latest A1C?

16:35.124 --> 16:38.040
- Daniel, I'm fine.
Look, I even got myself one

16:38.084 --> 16:41.304
of those continuous
glucose monitors.

16:41.348 --> 16:45.047
And my blood sugar
is under control.

16:45.091 --> 16:48.050
- I'm very glad to hear that.
- Thank you.

16:50.618 --> 16:52.359
- Just got Candace's labs back.

16:52.402 --> 16:57.451
Other than a slightly elevated
WBC, everything looks good.

16:57.494 --> 17:00.019
- Good.
This is unreal.

17:00.062 --> 17:01.542
- What's that?

17:01.585 --> 17:02.978
- So according
to Candace's chart,

17:03.022 --> 17:05.198
her Lupus hasn't been active
since 2016.

17:05.241 --> 17:07.722
You wouldn't know it
by her website though.

17:07.765 --> 17:09.854
It says she's been
in a flare-up the past month.

17:09.898 --> 17:12.944
Can't eat,
can't get out of bed.

17:12.988 --> 17:15.425
She's also soliciting
donations.

17:15.469 --> 17:17.601
Claims they're going
to Lupus research but...

17:17.645 --> 17:20.648
- You think she's pocketing
the money?

17:20.691 --> 17:22.171
- I don't know.

17:22.215 --> 17:24.913
You'd be surprised the lengths
people go to make a buck.

17:24.956 --> 17:27.698
- Yeah, anything's possible,
I guess.

17:27.742 --> 17:29.787
Anyway, I'm gonna go check
and see if the two-view

17:29.831 --> 17:32.051
of Candace's elbow is back.

17:32.094 --> 17:35.010
[solemn music]

17:35.054 --> 17:37.752
♪

17:37.795 --> 17:39.580
- Elaine, they're ready
for you in radiology.

17:39.623 --> 17:41.364
Maggie's gonna bring you up.

17:41.408 --> 17:44.498
- Ugh, nothing makes you
feel your age

17:44.541 --> 17:47.588
like being helped
into a wheelchair.

17:47.631 --> 17:50.286
- Nonsense.
- [sighs]

17:50.330 --> 17:53.985
- You're still young.
- Young at heart at least.

17:57.641 --> 17:59.208
- Would you like to accompany
your wife?

17:59.252 --> 18:01.602
- No, I'll wait here.
How long is it gonna take?

18:01.645 --> 18:03.343
I was planning to make
a paella tonight,

18:03.386 --> 18:06.694
and I still need to take
the chicken out of the freezer.

18:06.737 --> 18:10.915
- Let the rads resident
know we need a fast read.

18:10.959 --> 18:12.134
- Right.

18:12.178 --> 18:15.616
♪

18:15.659 --> 18:18.140
- Hey, so good news...

18:18.184 --> 18:21.230
the fine needle biopsy
came back and it's benign.

18:21.274 --> 18:24.407
- So that means
it's not cancer, right?

18:24.451 --> 18:25.930
- Correct.
- Oh, thank God.

18:25.974 --> 18:29.282
- However, the tumor does
extend into your upper chest.

18:29.325 --> 18:31.893
And it's enveloping several
of the major blood vessels

18:31.936 --> 18:33.590
that are coming off your heart,

18:33.634 --> 18:35.157
so you will need
a neck dissection--

18:35.201 --> 18:37.420
possible sternotomy--
to remove it.

18:37.464 --> 18:39.466
- The surgeon will make
an incision along your neck

18:39.509 --> 18:40.684
to excise the mass.

18:40.728 --> 18:42.251
Ideally, it'll come out
in one piece.

18:42.295 --> 18:44.601
But if not, the surgeon may
also need to open your chest.

18:44.645 --> 18:47.474
- Just so you know, we see a
high volume of both procedures

18:47.517 --> 18:49.040
here at Med
with excellent outcomes.

18:49.084 --> 18:52.696
- I read online that sometimes
these tumors are treated

18:52.740 --> 18:54.481
with medicine?

18:54.524 --> 18:56.961
- They are, yes.
Radioactive iodine.

18:57.005 --> 18:59.921
But I'm afraid
it's long past that point.

18:59.964 --> 19:02.750
The tumor's already too close
to your big blood vessels--

19:02.793 --> 19:04.795
- I've been okay so far.
- Gina, I think you should

19:04.839 --> 19:06.623
listen to the doctor.
- I'd like to at least start

19:06.667 --> 19:08.451
with medicine.

19:08.495 --> 19:10.671
- I'm not sure you're grasping
how serious this is.

19:10.714 --> 19:12.716
- I get it.

19:12.760 --> 19:15.023
- You know what, Gina,
this is a big decision.

19:15.066 --> 19:17.417
So why don't you take some time
to think about it

19:17.460 --> 19:18.853
and we'll check back later.

19:18.896 --> 19:21.247
Okay?
All right.

19:21.290 --> 19:25.512
♪

19:25.555 --> 19:27.818
- Radioactive iodine isn't
going to work fast enough.

19:27.862 --> 19:29.080
This thing's
a ticking time bomb.

19:29.124 --> 19:30.821
- Yeah, but we need
to tread lightly.

19:30.865 --> 19:31.996
I'm gonna go grab Dr. Charles.

19:32.040 --> 19:34.216
See if he can make
some headway.

19:34.260 --> 19:36.914
- So your white blood cell
count is slightly elevated.

19:36.958 --> 19:39.308
But that's pretty normal
following a trauma.

19:39.352 --> 19:40.701
It's likely from the stress.

19:40.744 --> 19:43.138
- And your elbow x-ray
was negative.

19:43.182 --> 19:45.575
You'll just wanna ice it
for a few days.

19:45.619 --> 19:48.317
- I feel like I should explain.
- You don't have to explain

19:48.361 --> 19:50.754
anything to us.
- Well, I launched this website

19:50.798 --> 19:52.887
a few months after
I was diagnosed with Lupus.

19:52.930 --> 19:56.934
- "When Life Gives You Lupus"?
- Oh, you saw it?

19:56.978 --> 19:59.502
Well, the only reason I haven't
advertised my remission

19:59.546 --> 20:03.767
is because...I mean, you saw
that woman who approached me.

20:03.811 --> 20:06.683
The website is a lifeline
for so many and I felt that,

20:06.727 --> 20:08.903
you know, bragging about
my remission--

20:08.946 --> 20:11.949
it would kind of dilute
the message.

20:11.993 --> 20:13.603
- And messaging is key, right?

20:13.647 --> 20:15.736
Especially when it comes
to fundraising.

20:15.779 --> 20:17.694
- Any questions for us,
Candace?

20:17.738 --> 20:20.393
- No, I don't think so.

20:20.436 --> 20:22.177
Oh, my God.

20:22.221 --> 20:24.266
- You okay?

20:24.310 --> 20:26.181
- You sure you didn't
lose consciousness?

20:26.225 --> 20:28.792
- Yeah, I'm pretty sure.
It all happened so fast though.

20:28.836 --> 20:32.361
- Yep, let's get a head CT
just to be safe.

20:32.405 --> 20:34.624
- Mm-hmm.

20:39.281 --> 20:41.109
- Mr. Foster,
I just wanted to let you know

20:41.152 --> 20:42.371
your wife will be down shortly.

20:42.415 --> 20:44.286
- Oh, how's Elaine's ankle?
Is it broken?

20:44.330 --> 20:46.332
- No, it's not; it's
just a sprain, fortunately.

20:46.375 --> 20:50.205
- Oh, good.
You're a runner, aren't you?

20:50.249 --> 20:53.121
- Sorry?
- It's not a trick question.

20:53.164 --> 20:55.036
- Uh, yes, I run.

20:55.079 --> 20:57.734
- Mm-hmm, knew it.
See, women of a certain age--

20:57.778 --> 20:59.301
how old are you?

20:59.345 --> 21:01.129
- I don't think that's any
of your business.

21:01.172 --> 21:02.870
- 32, 33?

21:02.913 --> 21:05.002
That's when women start to get
a little extra padding

21:05.046 --> 21:07.614
around the middle,
except runners.

21:07.657 --> 21:09.224
Good for you.

21:09.268 --> 21:11.792
- Excuse me.
- It's just a compliment.

21:11.835 --> 21:13.010
- Get your hand off me, please.

21:13.054 --> 21:14.795
- I'm not gonna bite.

21:14.838 --> 21:16.318
- I said let go.
- Would you--

21:16.362 --> 21:18.277
- Now!
- Just relax.

21:18.320 --> 21:21.236
[tense music]

21:21.280 --> 21:24.631
♪

21:24.674 --> 21:26.197
- What the hell are you doing?

21:26.241 --> 21:27.938
♪

21:27.982 --> 21:30.158
Jim, are you okay?

21:30.201 --> 21:31.202
- [grunts]

21:31.246 --> 21:33.944
♪

21:37.165 --> 21:37.339
.

21:37.383 --> 21:38.862
- Okay, so...

21:38.906 --> 21:40.037
where did he touch you?

21:40.081 --> 21:40.995
- What difference
does that make?

21:41.038 --> 21:42.126
- I'm--I'm just trying to get

21:42.170 --> 21:43.171
all the facts straight.

21:43.214 --> 21:44.868
- My forearm.
- Was he aware

21:44.912 --> 21:46.130
that this made you
uncomfortable?

21:46.174 --> 21:48.481
- I asked him repeatedly
to remove his hands.

21:48.524 --> 21:50.396
So yeah, I think that
should've clued him in.

21:50.439 --> 21:52.528
- Of course, but do you think
there's a chance that--

21:52.572 --> 21:53.573
- Peter.

21:53.616 --> 21:55.923
Enough.

21:55.966 --> 21:59.753
Dr. Hammer, I'm sorry and,
quite frankly, I'm at a loss.

21:59.796 --> 22:03.191
In all of the years
that I have known Jim Foster,

22:03.234 --> 22:06.890
I have never seen him behave
in a predatory manner.

22:06.934 --> 22:09.284
If I had, I never would have

22:09.328 --> 22:12.287
put you and Maggie
in this position.

22:12.331 --> 22:16.422
But please be assured
that you will be supported

22:16.465 --> 22:20.382
in whatever course of action
you wish to pursue.

22:20.426 --> 22:23.385
And should you decide
to press charges--

22:23.429 --> 22:25.518
- Oh, okay, whoa, whoa, whoa.
Now let's not get ahead

22:25.561 --> 22:27.520
of ourselves here.

22:27.563 --> 22:30.653
Okay, I think that our best bet
for all the parties involved--

22:30.697 --> 22:31.959
most importantly Dr. Hammer--

22:32.002 --> 22:33.743
to spare her
any further discomfort,

22:33.787 --> 22:37.399
would be to settle this without
involving law enforcement.

22:37.443 --> 22:40.141
- Peter, we are not going
to sweep this under the rug

22:40.184 --> 22:42.273
because Jim Foster is a donor.

22:42.317 --> 22:44.624
- Ms. Goodwin,
I appreciate the support.

22:44.667 --> 22:49.585
I do...but I'm not interested
in pressing charges anyway.

22:49.629 --> 22:52.588
- Well, that's your decision
to make, Dr. Hammer.

22:52.632 --> 22:57.114
But, with your permission, I'd
like to have a word with Jim.

22:57.158 --> 22:59.769
- Sharon, would you let...

22:59.813 --> 23:06.733
♪

23:14.349 --> 23:16.482
- Hey, Nancy, any word on--

23:16.525 --> 23:18.614
- The kid, Michael?
No.

23:18.658 --> 23:21.791
And the OR asked me to please
stop calling for updates.

23:21.835 --> 23:24.707
I'll let you know the minute he
gets out of surgery, Dr. Scott.

23:29.669 --> 23:32.106
- Hey, regarding Candace--
- Yeah, the techs just took her

23:32.149 --> 23:33.586
up to CT.

23:33.629 --> 23:36.240
- Oh, good, great.
Listen, I've been thinking...

23:36.284 --> 23:38.242
let's say Candace
is pocketing donations--

23:38.286 --> 23:39.940
- Oh, so you have evidence?

23:39.983 --> 23:41.463
- No, not yet.

23:41.507 --> 23:43.639
But if we call the charities
listed on her website,

23:43.683 --> 23:45.467
and they don't support
her claims--

23:45.511 --> 23:48.470
- No, man, I don't want
anything to do with this.

23:48.514 --> 23:51.821
- I would've thought you'd
at least be curious--as a cop.

23:51.865 --> 23:54.998
- I'm a doctor, not a cop.
And neither are you.

23:55.042 --> 23:57.523
Though you sure seem to get off
on acting like one, man.

23:59.438 --> 24:02.528
[contemplative music]

24:02.571 --> 24:03.616
♪

24:03.659 --> 24:05.444
- Psychiatry?

24:05.487 --> 24:08.272
Is this about the surgery?

24:08.316 --> 24:10.492
If you're here to tell me
that I'm not in my right mind

24:10.536 --> 24:13.321
or to try to force me to get--
- No, not at all.

24:13.364 --> 24:15.671
Not at all, Gina.
It's very clear that you have

24:15.715 --> 24:18.674
decisional capacity,
so nobody's gonna

24:18.718 --> 24:20.546
try and make you do something
you don't want to do.

24:20.589 --> 24:22.461
- Oh.

24:22.504 --> 24:24.898
Okay.

24:24.941 --> 24:26.769
♪

24:26.813 --> 24:29.729
I'm not saying that I won't
have the surgery...ever.

24:29.772 --> 24:31.295
I just...

24:31.339 --> 24:32.993
I just wanna wait.
- That's fine.

24:33.036 --> 24:35.474
We can talk about surgery later
if you want, but I just wanted

24:35.517 --> 24:38.215
to ask you when--when did you
first notice

24:38.259 --> 24:40.522
the growth on your neck?

24:40.566 --> 24:42.437
- A few months into COVID.
- Right.

24:42.481 --> 24:44.874
- That's why I didn't come in
for an appointment right away.

24:44.918 --> 24:47.050
It wasn't that big and...

24:47.094 --> 24:48.704
we were being told
to avoid hospitals

24:48.748 --> 24:51.707
unless it was an emergency.
- Certainly, I understand that.

24:51.751 --> 24:54.884
But later, you know,
when things opened up a bit...

24:54.928 --> 24:57.757
I mean, it started
to get a little bigger, right?

24:57.800 --> 25:00.586
- I just sort of hoped
that it would...

25:00.629 --> 25:03.110
go away on its own.
And I...

25:03.153 --> 25:04.807
I realize how insane
that sounds.

25:04.851 --> 25:06.766
- Mm, sounds hopeful.

25:06.809 --> 25:08.898
Nothing insane about hope.

25:08.942 --> 25:11.379
- I was so afraid of...

25:11.422 --> 25:14.251
what it could be
that I just...

25:14.295 --> 25:18.038
I just found it easier to...

25:18.081 --> 25:21.345
- Not think about it at all.
Oh, yes.

25:21.389 --> 25:23.478
It's very human.
- [coughing]

25:26.786 --> 25:30.529
♪

25:30.572 --> 25:32.443
- Oh.

25:32.487 --> 25:34.750
Dr. Marcel, coughing up
a little blood here.

25:34.794 --> 25:37.753
- I'm on it.
Dr. Taylor, get her on oxygen.

25:37.797 --> 25:39.581
Ten liters please.

25:39.625 --> 25:41.583
Trini, two of Morphine
and get me a basin.

25:41.627 --> 25:44.543
- What a load of BS.
I paid her a compliment,

25:44.586 --> 25:46.501
which apparently men aren't
allowed to do anymore

25:46.545 --> 25:47.981
without getting shoved
to the ground.

25:48.024 --> 25:50.287
- Listen, Jim, she said
you grabbed her by the arm--

25:50.331 --> 25:51.593
- She assaulted me.

25:51.637 --> 25:53.377
I should be pressing charges
against her.

25:53.421 --> 25:55.771
Can you believe this?
Well, I've had enough.

25:55.815 --> 25:57.773
If this is how you treat
your benefactors--

25:57.817 --> 26:01.081
- Jim, we are incredibly
grateful for your support; ho--

26:01.124 --> 26:04.127
- Yeah, yeah, you can consider
that well all dried up.

26:04.171 --> 26:05.607
In fact, find someone else

26:05.651 --> 26:09.089
to fund your hematology wing.
- Jim.

26:09.132 --> 26:12.353
- We are withdrawing
our pledge.

26:12.396 --> 26:14.485
Elaine, I'm getting the car.
I'll meet you out front.

26:14.529 --> 26:18.620
- Jim.
[sighs]

26:18.664 --> 26:21.623
Elaine?

26:21.667 --> 26:23.973
- A couple weeks ago,
a female grad student

26:24.017 --> 26:27.673
accused Jim of making a pass.

26:27.716 --> 26:29.500
I thought it had
to be a misunderstanding.

26:29.544 --> 26:33.635
He has never been accused
of misconduct.

26:33.679 --> 26:36.725
Is this some kind of a,
I don't know,

26:36.769 --> 26:38.335
midlife crisis?

26:38.379 --> 26:42.644
♪

26:42.688 --> 26:45.429
- Your head CT was clean.
No signs of a bleed.

26:45.473 --> 26:47.083
It was likely just a migraine--

26:47.127 --> 26:48.955
not uncommon
following a trauma.

26:48.998 --> 26:52.001
The nurse will be in shortly
with your discharge paperwork.

26:52.045 --> 26:54.656
- I'm not one of those people
who pretends to be sick to,

26:54.700 --> 26:56.702
like, feed their ego
or scam people out of money,

26:56.745 --> 26:58.573
I swear.

27:00.706 --> 27:02.490
- I believe you.

27:02.533 --> 27:04.187
I can usually tell when
someone's shooting straight

27:04.231 --> 27:06.189
with me, and I think you are.

27:06.233 --> 27:09.671
- Thanks.
- But I will say...

27:09.715 --> 27:13.370
your fear that your message
will lose its impact

27:13.414 --> 27:15.590
if it's not delivered
from the trenches?

27:15.634 --> 27:17.766
I don't know if that's true.

27:17.810 --> 27:19.681
If anything,
you give people hope.

27:19.725 --> 27:23.163
- I've considered that, but if
I'm being completely honest,

27:23.206 --> 27:25.339
it's not just about
the messaging.

27:25.382 --> 27:27.210
Before I was diagnosed
with Lupus,

27:27.254 --> 27:28.951
I was pretty much a loner,
but...

27:28.995 --> 27:32.172
this disease, it gave me
a community for the first time

27:32.215 --> 27:33.782
in my life, and...

27:33.826 --> 27:35.871
if they know
that I'm in remission...

27:35.915 --> 27:38.744
- You'll feel like an outsider.
Yeah, I get it.

27:38.787 --> 27:39.832
♪

27:39.875 --> 27:42.182
But, you know...

27:42.225 --> 27:44.445
walking a path
that isn't yours?

27:44.488 --> 27:45.881
There's a steep price
to that too.

27:45.925 --> 27:47.143
- I know.

27:47.187 --> 27:48.449
I hate lying
to all these people.

27:48.492 --> 27:49.842
- Yeah, just--

27:49.885 --> 27:51.974
- Dr. Scott?
Just wanted to let you know

27:52.018 --> 27:53.367
your patient's out of surgery.

27:53.410 --> 27:55.848
- Oh, thank you.

27:57.458 --> 27:58.894
- No, go ahead, I'm fine.

27:58.938 --> 28:00.069
- You sure?

28:00.113 --> 28:01.462
- Yeah.

28:01.505 --> 28:03.072
Thank you, Dr. Scott,
for everything.

28:03.116 --> 28:04.508
- You got it.

28:04.552 --> 28:06.859
Take care, Candace.

28:06.902 --> 28:08.295
- Hey, Nancy!

28:08.338 --> 28:09.644
How'd Michael do?
- [sighs]

28:09.688 --> 28:11.080
The nurse didn't say.

28:11.124 --> 28:13.256
Sorry.

28:13.300 --> 28:15.911
♪

28:15.955 --> 28:17.478
- Just a moment, please.

28:17.521 --> 28:19.393
- Is everything all right,
Elaine?

28:19.436 --> 28:21.221
- I just want to speak
to Dr. Hammer.

28:21.264 --> 28:23.440
- Dr. Hammer.

28:23.484 --> 28:24.485
Over here.

28:24.528 --> 28:30.012
♪

28:30.056 --> 28:32.580
- I'm sorry, Dr. Hammer.

28:32.623 --> 28:35.365
I'm not making excuses for him.
I have none.

28:35.409 --> 28:41.110
But I just...want you to know
he has never been like this.

28:41.154 --> 28:42.546
I...

28:42.590 --> 28:45.245
I don't know what happened
to the man I married.

28:45.288 --> 28:49.249
♪

28:49.292 --> 28:52.078
I'm ready.

28:52.121 --> 28:53.383
- I'll be in touch, Elaine.

28:53.427 --> 28:56.125
♪

28:56.169 --> 28:57.648
Dr. Hammer?

28:57.692 --> 28:59.346
- When they first got here,
Elaine said that he'd been

28:59.389 --> 29:01.435
out of sorts.
- Jim?

29:01.478 --> 29:03.785
- And that he'd lost
his sense of smell.

29:03.829 --> 29:05.656
And when I pushed him away,
he couldn't seem

29:05.700 --> 29:07.702
to find his balance.

29:07.746 --> 29:09.791
Oh, my God.
We can't let them leave.

29:09.835 --> 29:11.575
- What? Why?
What is it?

29:11.619 --> 29:13.142
- We have to get them back here
right now, please.

29:13.186 --> 29:14.535
- Okay.

29:17.973 --> 29:18.191
.

29:18.234 --> 29:20.759
- Hey, Michael.
- I remember you.

29:20.802 --> 29:23.500
- Mm-hmm.
- Surgery went very well.

29:23.544 --> 29:26.503
- Hey, Michael, we're gonna
move you over to the PICU.

29:26.547 --> 29:28.114
Your mom and dad are
waiting to see you.

29:28.157 --> 29:30.246
- Am I in trouble?

29:30.290 --> 29:33.423
- I think they're just happy
that you're okay.

29:33.467 --> 29:36.992
- But, hey, maybe you learned
something about guns today?

29:37.036 --> 29:38.646
- Not toys.
- Right.

29:38.689 --> 29:42.389
I mean, besides, what superhero
do you know that has a gun?

29:42.432 --> 29:45.827
We don't need 'em.

29:45.871 --> 29:46.872
[growling]

29:46.915 --> 29:48.656
[laughs]

29:52.573 --> 29:56.142
- You know, if you hadn't been
there on the scene...

29:56.185 --> 29:57.970
kid would have bled out,
no question.

29:58.013 --> 30:00.450
You saved his life, Dr. Scott.

30:04.106 --> 30:07.588
- Back shortly, okay?

30:07.631 --> 30:08.981
[sighs]

30:09.024 --> 30:10.852
- She still wants to wait
on the surgery.

30:10.896 --> 30:13.289
- If nearly drowning in her own
blood didn't convince her...

30:13.333 --> 30:15.683
- How does someone let it get
to this point?

30:15.726 --> 30:16.902
- You know, the mind can have

30:16.945 --> 30:19.382
this mysterious
and profound ability

30:19.426 --> 30:21.297
to convince us
to put off almost anything.

30:21.341 --> 30:22.864
- Yeah.

30:22.908 --> 30:24.735
- Why is that?

30:24.779 --> 30:28.348
- One line of thinking is that
we have this bizarre tendency

30:28.391 --> 30:31.568
to disassociate
from our future selves.

30:31.612 --> 30:33.919
There's this really interesting
experiment at Princeton

30:33.962 --> 30:36.182
where two groups of students

30:36.225 --> 30:38.140
were recruited to drink what
was described to them as

30:38.184 --> 30:41.013
this disgusting,
foul-smelling liquid.

30:41.056 --> 30:42.492
Now they were given a choice

30:42.536 --> 30:44.451
about how much
they could drink.

30:44.494 --> 30:47.236
And the group that was told
they had to drink it that day

30:47.280 --> 30:48.672
agreed to drink very little.

30:48.716 --> 30:50.413
But the group that was told
to come back

30:50.457 --> 30:51.850
in a couple of months
and drink it

30:51.893 --> 30:53.373
agreed to drink much more.
- Right.

30:53.416 --> 30:54.896
So they can kick the can down
the road.

30:54.940 --> 30:56.289
- Right.
- Right.

30:56.332 --> 30:58.247
Okay, so how do we
solve the disconnect?

30:58.291 --> 31:01.555
- You gotta find a way to make
her future self feel...

31:01.598 --> 31:02.948
more tangible to her.

31:02.991 --> 31:05.124
More real.

31:06.647 --> 31:08.170
- There it is.

31:08.214 --> 31:11.957
An olfactory groove meningioma.
- Hmm.

31:12.000 --> 31:14.611
I had a patient early on
in my nursing days

31:14.655 --> 31:16.222
with this type of tumor.

31:16.265 --> 31:19.268
Caused a total personality
change.

31:19.312 --> 31:21.009
- It has a profound
disinhibition effect

31:21.053 --> 31:22.750
on the brain.

31:22.793 --> 31:25.274
And its proximity to
the olfactory nerve, that--

31:25.318 --> 31:27.973
- Explains Jim's loss of smell.

31:28.016 --> 31:30.932
- I'll page neurosurgery
for a consult.

31:30.976 --> 31:33.326
- Do you want to deliver
the news?

31:33.369 --> 31:36.720
- I think maybe it's better
coming from a friend.

31:36.764 --> 31:39.158
- Ah, copy that.

31:39.201 --> 31:43.989
♪

31:44.032 --> 31:45.207
- Gina.

31:45.251 --> 31:47.731
We wanna show you something.

31:47.775 --> 31:51.257
♪

31:51.300 --> 31:53.912
- Is that me?
What--

31:53.955 --> 31:55.217
Where did you get that picture?

31:55.261 --> 31:57.306
- Your friend Liza sent it
to us.

31:57.350 --> 32:00.440
My daughter she just--she loves
these aging filters and--

32:00.483 --> 32:01.963
- What does this
have to do with?

32:02.007 --> 32:05.097
- Well, we wanted you to take
a look at this photo...

32:05.140 --> 32:08.883
and think about a future
version of yourself.

32:08.927 --> 32:10.798
You know, what...

32:10.841 --> 32:12.321
what is her life like?

32:12.365 --> 32:14.280
Who does she care about?

32:14.323 --> 32:15.455
What does she love?

32:15.498 --> 32:19.328
- [voice breaking]
I don't want to.

32:21.069 --> 32:24.681
- What is it, Gina?

32:24.725 --> 32:27.684
- I haven't thought about
the future...

32:27.728 --> 32:30.774
in a really long time.

32:30.818 --> 32:33.168
- Why do you think that is?

32:35.127 --> 32:39.348
- Because what if...

32:39.392 --> 32:42.221
what if I don't have one?

32:42.264 --> 32:44.397
- What if you do?

32:44.440 --> 32:46.660
What would you want it
to look like?

32:46.703 --> 32:50.142
[somber music]

32:50.185 --> 32:52.927
- I guess...

32:52.971 --> 32:57.714
I see myself with a kid.
Maybe two.

32:57.758 --> 33:00.195
Living someplace warm.

33:00.239 --> 33:01.805
I have this dream.

33:01.849 --> 33:05.331
I've always wanted to open up
an outdoor bookshop.

33:05.374 --> 33:08.073
It's impractical in Chicago,
I know, but...

33:08.116 --> 33:10.597
- Not if you're living
someplace warmer.

33:10.640 --> 33:12.381
♪

33:12.425 --> 33:14.905
- Hey, Gina.
Look, I know you're scared.

33:14.949 --> 33:17.212
I get it.

33:17.256 --> 33:19.867
But if you continue
to postpone surgery,

33:19.910 --> 33:21.869
you're denying yourself
a shot at what sounds like

33:21.912 --> 33:23.958
a really great future.

33:24.002 --> 33:28.397
♪

33:28.441 --> 33:30.051
- We're gonna give you
a little time, okay?

33:30.095 --> 33:32.314
You wanna hold onto this
for a bit?

33:32.358 --> 33:39.495
♪

33:41.802 --> 33:44.500
- Wait.

33:48.722 --> 33:51.812
- Gina?

33:51.855 --> 33:53.292
- I'll have the surgery.

33:53.335 --> 33:55.685
♪

33:55.729 --> 33:58.732
- Okay.

33:58.775 --> 34:00.038
♪

34:00.081 --> 34:01.561
- Did Candace leave already?

34:01.604 --> 34:04.738
- Yeah, discharged her.
Ay, come take a look at this.

34:04.781 --> 34:06.783
She came clean
to her followers.

34:06.827 --> 34:09.960
♪

34:10.004 --> 34:12.920
- Unfortunately, she's wrong.

34:12.963 --> 34:15.705
Her Lupus is active again.
She's no longer in remission.

34:15.749 --> 34:21.450
♪

34:24.932 --> 34:25.063
.

34:25.106 --> 34:26.716
- My Lupus is active again?

34:26.760 --> 34:28.153
- Unfortunately, yes.

34:28.196 --> 34:31.330
I ran another set of labs
which confirmed it.

34:31.373 --> 34:33.071
- How did you know?

34:33.114 --> 34:35.116
- So you told us this morning
you did not see the car

34:35.160 --> 34:37.379
before it hit you, right?
So that got me wondering

34:37.423 --> 34:40.165
if peripheral vision loss
could be to blame.

34:40.208 --> 34:41.992
Combined with your elevated
white blood count

34:42.036 --> 34:44.430
and head pain...if your Lupus
had become active again

34:44.473 --> 34:47.520
and was attacking your brain--
- But I thought my head CT

34:47.563 --> 34:48.782
was negative.
- It was.

34:48.825 --> 34:51.045
But swelling wouldn't be
visible on a CT.

34:51.089 --> 34:53.395
- That's right.
We're gonna send you for an MRI

34:53.439 --> 34:54.831
to see exactly what's going on,

34:54.875 --> 34:56.877
but all signs point
to brain inflammation

34:56.920 --> 34:59.619
and optic neuritis
due to underlying Lupus.

35:01.055 --> 35:03.101
- I guess this is what I
deserve for crying wolf

35:03.144 --> 35:05.625
all these years.

35:05.668 --> 35:07.670
God, you should see
the comments under my post.

35:07.714 --> 35:09.759
They're so hurt and angry.

35:09.803 --> 35:11.892
And now if I tell them
it's active again,

35:11.935 --> 35:15.156
nobody's gonna care.
Nobody's gonna believe me.

35:15.200 --> 35:18.899
- Listen, I know you feel like
you lost your tribe right now.

35:18.942 --> 35:22.381
But understanding?
It's a process.

35:22.424 --> 35:24.165
You did your part.

35:24.209 --> 35:25.993
Laying out your truth.

35:26.036 --> 35:28.169
Now give them a chance
to get there.

35:28.213 --> 35:31.085
Those who you want
in the trenches with you,

35:31.129 --> 35:34.044
they'll come around.

35:34.088 --> 35:41.051
♪

35:41.095 --> 35:43.793
- Good luck, Gina.

35:43.837 --> 35:45.839
- Oh, hey, Daniel.
Glad I caught you.

35:45.882 --> 35:48.407
I noticed that you didn't log
any patients

35:48.450 --> 35:49.756
into the new portal today.

35:49.799 --> 35:51.410
If you're having trouble
navigating the platform,

35:51.453 --> 35:53.542
I'd be happy to get somebody
from IT to walk you through it.

35:53.586 --> 35:54.891
- Oh, you know,
I really appreciate that,

35:54.935 --> 35:56.328
but it's not gonna
be necessary.

35:56.371 --> 35:57.938
I'm not gonna be using it.

35:57.981 --> 35:59.505
- Oh, yeah.

35:59.548 --> 36:01.159
I know it's a pain, but, uh...

36:01.202 --> 36:03.900
- Well, not that it's a pain.
It just-- it just doesn't make

36:03.944 --> 36:05.989
a whole lot of sense
for psychiatry.

36:06.033 --> 36:07.252
- Uh-huh.

36:07.295 --> 36:09.123
- We can't just do
a three-minute evaluation

36:09.167 --> 36:11.169
and, like, fire off a script,
you know?

36:11.212 --> 36:13.040
Gotta spend more time
with the patients.

36:13.083 --> 36:15.173
Not really any way around it.
- Yeah.

36:15.216 --> 36:16.826
- This young woman I was
working with today--

36:16.870 --> 36:19.089
I mean honestly, if I hadn't
taken the time to understand

36:19.133 --> 36:21.222
and then address the root cause
of her issue,

36:21.266 --> 36:24.007
she probably wouldn't be
heading off to undergo,

36:24.051 --> 36:26.227
you know, surgery--probably
gonna save her life, so...

36:26.271 --> 36:28.664
- Hey, listen, I hear you.
I think you're right.

36:28.708 --> 36:31.232
- Okay.
Well, terrific.

36:31.276 --> 36:33.539
- Given the necessity
for speed in the ED,

36:33.582 --> 36:35.802
maybe psychiatry
just doesn't belong here.

36:35.845 --> 36:39.022
- [laughs]
You think?

36:39.066 --> 36:42.200
You go ahead and run that up
the flag pole, buddy.

36:44.593 --> 36:48.162
- Neurosurgery started Jim
on steroids to reduce the edema

36:48.206 --> 36:49.468
in his brain.

36:49.511 --> 36:52.166
You should also know that
he finally owned up

36:52.210 --> 36:53.559
to what he did.

36:53.602 --> 36:56.997
And asked me to pass along
his apology.

36:57.040 --> 36:59.217
- I'll admit my guard was up
from the minute you said

36:59.260 --> 37:00.740
they were donors.

37:00.783 --> 37:02.350
I've just seen too many people
use their money

37:02.394 --> 37:04.004
as leverage over others,
you know?

37:04.047 --> 37:07.529
- Well, my condolences
to anyone who ever tries that

37:07.573 --> 37:10.880
with you again.
[laughter]

37:10.924 --> 37:13.622
[soft dramatic music]

37:13.666 --> 37:15.102
- Hey, Maggie?
- Yeah.

37:15.145 --> 37:17.147
- Mind if I take off
a little early today?

37:17.191 --> 37:19.411
I need to take care
of some personal business.

37:19.454 --> 37:21.456
- No, go ahead.
- Thank you.

37:21.500 --> 37:24.111
- All right.
- I'll see you tomorrow.

37:24.154 --> 37:27.680
♪

37:27.723 --> 37:31.074
- Hey.
- Hey.

37:31.118 --> 37:32.815
- [chuckles]

37:32.859 --> 37:34.513
- Wait, is that you,
Dr. Marcel?

37:34.556 --> 37:36.428
- In 30 or so years, yeah.

37:36.471 --> 37:37.994
I guess.

37:38.038 --> 37:40.606
- I thought you weren't into
thinking about the future.

37:40.649 --> 37:42.042
"Planning leads
to expectations,

37:42.085 --> 37:44.044
which can lead
to disappointments."

37:44.087 --> 37:46.525
- Oh, you were
paying attention, huh?

37:46.568 --> 37:48.440
Yeah, but I don't know.

37:48.483 --> 37:50.659
Maybe you're onto something.

37:50.703 --> 37:53.575
Maybe it's not
such a bad idea...

37:53.619 --> 37:55.795
giving some thought as to...

37:55.838 --> 37:57.666
where I might want to end up.

37:57.710 --> 38:00.321
Right?

38:00.365 --> 38:03.629
- Right.

38:03.672 --> 38:10.810
♪

38:13.116 --> 38:16.816
- Dr. Halstead, hi.
I'm, uh, Jessa Rinaldi.

38:16.859 --> 38:19.340
I'm a device rep at Vasik Labs.

38:19.384 --> 38:21.560
- Oh, hi.
Nice to meet you.

38:21.603 --> 38:24.824
- Dr. Cooper called my boss
today singing your praises.

38:24.867 --> 38:27.566
And a good word from Matt
goes a long way at Vasik.

38:27.609 --> 38:29.524
- I am honored.

38:29.568 --> 38:32.962
- I would love to talk to you
about one of our products,

38:33.006 --> 38:36.705
the Vas-COM.
It measures cardiac function--

38:36.749 --> 38:38.316
uh...output.

38:38.359 --> 38:42.711
It measures cardiac output
by, um...by...

38:42.755 --> 38:46.149
Well, it--it tells doctors when
patients need additional...

38:46.193 --> 38:47.237
medicine?

38:47.281 --> 38:49.065
I'm sorry,
that's not right either.

38:49.109 --> 38:50.632
- It's okay.
I'm familiar with the Vas-COM.

38:50.676 --> 38:52.678
- You are? Okay, great.

38:52.721 --> 38:55.376
Bottom line, we at Vasik
want to make the Vas-COM

38:55.420 --> 38:57.335
the new standard of care,
and we could really use

38:57.378 --> 38:59.380
your help promoting it
across departments?

38:59.424 --> 39:01.077
Doctor Cooper said that you

39:01.121 --> 39:03.384
could be a real asset...
in that regard...

39:03.428 --> 39:04.907
if you're sold on the device.

39:04.951 --> 39:07.562
And Vasik would, of course,
compensate you

39:07.606 --> 39:09.782
for your time and your effort.

39:09.825 --> 39:12.306
All above board, of course.

39:12.350 --> 39:13.525
♪

39:13.568 --> 39:15.614
- I am definitely interested.

39:15.657 --> 39:17.050
- You are?
Okay, great.

39:17.093 --> 39:20.314
Um, here,
let me give you my card.

39:20.358 --> 39:27.277
♪

39:35.851 --> 39:37.418
- Hey, Mom?

39:37.462 --> 39:38.637
It's me.

39:38.680 --> 39:45.818
♪

39:52.477 --> 39:55.218
It's 1,200.

39:55.262 --> 39:59.484
♪

39:59.527 --> 40:01.050
- Hey.

40:01.094 --> 40:01.877
Stevie!

40:01.921 --> 40:05.054
Stevie, wait.

40:05.098 --> 40:08.449
You're okay with me using it
on the van?

40:08.493 --> 40:11.670
- I'd prefer--you already know
what I'd prefer.

40:11.713 --> 40:14.194
But it's yours.

40:14.237 --> 40:16.544
No strings.
Do what you want with it, Mom.

40:16.588 --> 40:22.202
♪

40:22.245 --> 40:24.509
- Thank you.

40:24.552 --> 40:26.380
- Yeah.

40:26.424 --> 40:28.687
♪

40:28.730 --> 40:32.386
Can we get dinner somewhere?

40:32.430 --> 40:34.997
We don't have to go
to a restaurant or anything.

40:35.041 --> 40:37.870
We could just get take-out
and bring it back here?

40:37.913 --> 40:39.959
♪

40:40.002 --> 40:42.657
- Yeah.
All right.

40:42.701 --> 40:44.877
♪

40:44.920 --> 40:47.227
Let me grab my backpack.

40:47.270 --> 40:54.190
♪

41:07.726 --> 41:08.117
.

41:08.161 --> 41:10.859
[dramatic music]

41:10.903 --> 41:18.084
